        "text": "Hoshang Shah (1406–1435 CE) was the first independent ruler of the Muzaffarid Dynasty of Malwa. He was the son of Dilawar Khan Ghori, who was a court member of Delhi Sultan Firoz Shah Tughlaq. Hoshang Shah Gori ascended to the throne in 1406 AD and declared his independence. He fought various battles with Gujarat Sultanate and he was known as Alp Khan before becoming the monarch of Malwa. In this article, we will discuss the Important Ruler of the Muzaffarid Dynasty in Malwa Hoshang Shah (1406–1435 CE) which will be helpful for UPSC exam preparation.\n\nBackground\n\nHoshang Shah - Background\n\nHoshang Shah was the Malwa Sultanate and the first official ruler of the Muzaffarid Dynasty.\n\nHoshang Shah Gori was also known as Alp Khan before becoming the monarch of Malwa. He assumed the title Hoshang Shah after came to the throne.\n\nDilawar Khan Ghori, Hoshang Shah’s father, was a member of Sultan Firozshah Tughlaq Delhi's court.\n\nDilawar Khan Gori was appointed governor of Malwa, by Firoz Shah Tughlaq.\n\nHe had effectively arrived in Mandu in 1401 as the first King of Malwa, while not declaring himself an independent king.\n\nLater on, Hoshang Shah came to power and declared independence from the Sultans of Delhi. For thirty years, he ruled from 1406 to 1435 AD.\n\nReign\n\nReign of Hoshang Shah\n\nSultan Muzaffar Shah of the Muzaffarid dynasty of Gujarat invaded the Hoshang soon after his accession.\n\nIn medieval times, Malwa was the strongest rival of the Gujarat Sultanate.\n\nHoshang Shah was defeated during the invasion and taken prisoner by Muzaffar Shah.\n\nBut later on, Hoshang Shah's kingdom was returned and he moved his capital from Dhar to Mandu.\n\nHoshang Shah defeated and murdered the Narsingh Rai of Kherla, a vassal of Bahmani monarch Ahmad Shah (1422-35 AD).\n\nMuzaffarid Sultan’s Shihabuddin Ahmad Shah was compelled to depart Mandu as a result of the attacks.\n\nHe also surrounded Gagron Fort (Jhalawar district of Rajasthan). However, Mubarak Shah, the king of the Sayyid Dynasty, freed the sieged fort, and the effort of Hoshang Shah to take Gwalior collapsed.\n\nHe followed the policy of religious toleration.\n\nHoshang Shah died in 1435 AD and is buried in Mandu.\n\nThe city of Hoshangabad in Madhya Pradesh, which was named after Hoshang Shah, is now officially known as Narmadapuram.\n\nHoshang Shah's Tomb\n\nHoshang Shah's Tomb\n\nThe tomb is a marble structure built in honour of ruler Hoshang Shah.\n\nAccording to the inscription, the tomb was built in the 15th century in Mandu, Madhya Pradesh.\n\nThe tomb was so exquisite that Shah Jahan sent four of his architects to design the Taj Mahal before it was built.\n\nHoshang's Tomb is regarded as one of the oldest marble edifices and the most refined examples of Afghan architecture.\n\nConclusion\n\nConclusion\n\nHoshang Shah was Malwa's first legitimate Muslim ruler. He adopted a religious tolerance policy and many Rajputs were invited by him to settle in Malwa. According to the inscription on the Lalitpur temple, there were no restrictions on temple construction. He favoured the Jains, who were the area's leading merchants and bankers. He founded Hoshangabad in Madhya Pradesh and also turned Mandu into one of India's most formidable forts."
